Angular Developer Testing - Developer Testing (for me) means: - Writing tests AS we write our application - MUCH easier than waiting until the end. - We often have to write tests for "fictional" situations that are hard to simulate in "reality" - Service / Network failures - Sometimes we don't want to deadlocked on doing our work because it depends on a service that isn't actually available yet. - Modes - - components that show data from APIs have these standard "modes" - Ideal: What it should look like if both the API and the data from the API are present. - Loading: What it should look like if the API hasn't returned data yet. - Empty: What it should look like if the API call succeeded but no data was returned. - Error Mode: Something went wrong with the API call.Types or Levels of Testing:Testing through the User Interface: - run the application and test it as if the user was experiencing the app - What we do naturally as developers - alt-tabbing back and forth to make sure it is working. - we humans stink at doing monotonous things over and over consistently.Component Testing - - Isolated components. Service Test - testing our services(guards, pipes, all the Angular thingies!)"Code Coverage" TimeVelocityUnit TestsIntegratione2emanuale2e are HARD "Inner Loop"Feedback Loops: - Inner Loop - everything that happens BEFORE we push our code to the repo (pipeline) - Outer Loop - everything that happens AFTER we push our to the repo (pipeline)"Static Testing": - using things like es-lint to keep us on the right path. - using your language (TypeScript) to make invalid states either - impossible - or unlikely
